text.tspan: In addition to creating the first computerized
airline booking system, Berezin created the
world’s first word processor in 1971. Realizing
that because of her gender she wouldn’t be
able to move up in the industry, she also
founded her own company, Redactron, to get
her inventions on the market.

text.tspan: In 1978, while working for NASA, Barbara Askins was
tasked with finding a way to improve the quality of
photos taken from space. Her method of enhancing
photo negatives was far more widely applicable, as
it could be used to clarify photos after they were
already developed. Her technology has been adapted
for use with X-rays and historical photo restoration.

text.data-name: CLU is a programming language created by Barabara Liskov in 1975. While it did not find extensive use, it introduced many features that are used widely now, and is seen as a step in the development of object-oriented programming. Key contributions include
text.tspan: CLU is a programming language created by Barabara Liskov in
1975. While it did not find extensive use, it introduced many
features that are used widely now, and is seen as a step in the
development of object-oriented programming. Key
contributions include abstract data types,call-by-sharing,
iterators, multiple return values, type-safe parameterized types,
and type-safe variant types.

text.data-name: In 1973, Rosella Bjornson became the first female pilot for a commercial airline in North America. Her first flight as a pilot was from Thompson, Manitoba to Winnipeg, on a Transair Fokker F-28.

text.data-name: A major piece of evidence for the presence of dark matter in the Universe was discovered by Vera Rubin from observations of galactic rotation curves in the early 1970s. Her results suggested that Newtonian gravity does not apply universally or that, conser
text.tspan: A major piece of evidence for the presence of dark
matter in the Universe was discovered by Vera Rubin
from observations of galactic rotation curves in the
early 1970s. Her results suggested that Newtonian
gravity does not apply universally or that,
conservatively, upwards of 50% of the mass of
galaxies was contained in the relatively dark halo.
Her results have since been confirmed despite being
met with skepticism initially.
